Upload to ALL necessary QA platforms
All SWMS soft copies signed & hard copy printed & filed in the ‘on site’ paper folder

Tier 3: 1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
Tier 4: 1.1 - So far as reasonably practicable, all workers carrying out construction work on the project have been made aware of the content of the WHS management plan, including any updates, and their right to inspect the plan.

Tier 3: 1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
Tier 4: 1.2 - All workers carrying out construction work have received the general construction induction training.

Tier 3: 1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
Tier 4: 1.3 - Workers have been informed of the site-specific health and safety rules.

Tier 3: 1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
Tier 4: 1.4 - Suitable and adequate information, training, and instruction has been provided to workers in relation to work they are carrying out.

Tier 3: 1. Administrative, training and risk management requirements
Tier 4: 1.5 - Personal protective equipment (PPE) is being worn in accordance with the projects requirements.
2.1 - A safe work method statement (SWMS) has been prepared for each high risk construction work activity that is underway or about to commence.
2.2 - Workers have reviewed and signed off on the relevant SWMS
2.3 - High risk construction work activities are being carried out in accordance with the relevant SWMS.
3.1 - The work environment has been maintained such that it is clean and in a safe condition.
3.2 - Work areas are clearly identified and separated as necessary so that work can be undertaken safely.
3.3 - Lighting at the workplace is sufficient to allow:
3.4 - The workplace has sufficient ventilation to enable workers to carry out work without risk to health and safety.
3.5 - The entries, exits, and access ways in the workplace are kept clean and clear of materials and waste.
3.6 - A safe system has been implemented for the collection, storage, and disposal of excess or waste materials.
3.7 - Sufficient area has been allocated to safely store materials or plant for the construction work.
3.8 - Protruding objects that are a hazard have been made safe (e.g. exposed nails, vertical reinforcing steel).
3.9 - Adequate facilities have been provided for workers, including toilets, drinking water, washing facilities, and eating facilities.
3.10 - First aid equipment has been provided for the workplace and is accessible to each worker.
4.1 - For each hazard associated with a confined space, a competent person completed ASSES-05 Confined Spaces Risk.
4.2 - Prior to commencing the works, FORM-003 Entry Permit Confined Spaces has been completed and approved.
4.3 - Appropriate signage has been erected for all confined spaces.

4.4 - First aid procedures and rescue procedures to be followed in accordance with POLICY-006 Confined Spaces Rescue in the event of an emergency in a confined space have been developed and practiced to ensure they are efficient and effective.
4.5 - Workers required to work in or around a confined space have been provided with information, instruction, and training in relation to the:
5.1 - A SWMS is available for all high risk construction work that involves a risk of a person falling more than 2m that has commenced or is about to commence.
5.2 - Where a risk of fall of less than 2m exists:
5.3 - Where a risk of fall of at least 2m exists, control measures have been used which:
5.4 - Ladders are not used to support a weight greater than that for which they have been designed.
5.6 - Scaffolding has been erected by appropriately licensed workers.
5.7 - Scaffolding is or has been erected and/or dismantled so as to eliminate or minimise the risk of falling at least 2m to people carrying out the work, in accordance with the regulations
5.8 - Safe access to and egress from scaffold has been provided during erection, use, and dismantling.
5.9 - Written confirmation from a competent person stating that the construction of a particular scaffold has been completed, has been obtained prior to the use of that particular scaffold.
5.10 - REGISTER-007 Plant and Equipment is up to date and includes all mobile plant in use.
5.11 - CHECK-004 Pre-Start Plant and Equipment has been completed for all mobile plant in use on delivery to site.
5.12 - CHECK-005 Regular Plant and Equipment has been completed for all mobile plant prior to commencing operation of the plant that day.
5.13 - Mobile plant operators hold the appropriate high risk work licence.
5.14 - Where there is a possibility of powered mobile plant colliding with pedestrians or other powered mobile plant, a warning device has been fitted.
6.1 - Electrical leads are arranged to avoid damage.
6.2 - Electrical equipment has been inspected, testing, and tagged in accordance with AS/NZS 3012 Electrical installations – Construction and demolition sites.
7.1 - All hazardous chemicals that are used, handled, or stored at the workplace are correctly labelled.
7.2 - A safety data sheet (SDS) exists and is available for inspection for each hazardous chemical used, handled, or stored at the workplace.
7.3 - A register of hazardous chemicals used, handled, or stored at the workplace has been prepared in accordance with the regulations and is kept at the workplace.
7.4 - A spill containment system has been implemented in each part of the workplace where there is a risk from a spill or leak of a hazardous chemical.

column13: 1 - CABLE TYPE & SIZE TO DESIGN CRITERIA - AS1670.1-2018 Have a cross sectional area of no less than 0.75mm2 AS3000
2 - CABLE HEIGHTS & LOCATION ADEQUATE FOR FIT OFF - AS1670.1-2018: internal domestic and office situations where cabling is mounted on walls at heights above 1.5m AS3000
3 - CABLE FIXED TO SPECIFIED REQUIREMENTS - AS3000-2018: Where a wiring system is not resting on a continuous surface it shall be supported by suitable means in accordance with Clause 3.3.9
4 - DETECTOR BASES FITTED OFF - AS1670, AS1668: Detectors that can be contaminated by construction works should not be fitted unless suitably protected until the construction works are completed.
5 - DETECTOR HEADS INSTALLED & TYPE CHECKED - Detector type to appropriate location. Installed to Latest RCP

6 - MANUAL CALL POINTS INSTALLED - AS1670.1-2018: An MCP shall be mounted between 750 mm and 1100 mm above floor level and a clear space of 600 mm shall be provided in a semi-circle in front of the MCP.
7 - STROBES FITTED OFF - AS1670.1-2018: Check with Design Drawing and/or RCP
8 - SPEAKERS INSTALLED - AS1670: Check with Design Drawing and/or RCP
9 - WARDEN INTERCOM PHONES - AS1670.4-2018: The WIP handset shall be mounted at a height of not less than 1200 mm and not more than 1800 mm above finished floor level.

10 - SPRINKLER INTERFACES FITTED OFF - AS1670.1-2018: The ‘end-to-end’ test should include the activation of associated detection devices to confirm that all required functions operate correctly in accordance with the system interface matrix.
11 - FIRE RATING TO PENETRATIONS CORRECT - AS4072.1-2018: Ensure correct Test Report is used – refer to FRL requirements on wall selection
12 - LABELS AFFIXED - AS4072.1-2018: The label should be positioned close to the service penetration
13 - ACOUSTIC PENETRATION SEALING - AS4072.1-2018: Sound proofing sealant may be used depending on dB Level requirements
14 - CABLE TRAY BRACKET SPACING - AS3000-2018: Where a wiring system is not resting on a continuous surface it shall be supported by suitable means in accordance with Clause 3.3.9

resource: ITPS-004 Fire Alarm and EWIS Commissioning

column13: 1 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING OF ZONING - AS1670.1-2018: Ensure Detectors are activated when tested and correctly indicates on the detectors and at the FDCIE

2 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING OF SMOKE AND THERMALS - AS1670.1-2018: Aspirating detectors measure and record the transport time (TT) from the most disadvantaged sampling point for each sampling pipe or branch.

3 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING OF MCPS - AS1670.1-2018: (i) the correct operation of each manual call point; (ii) that the activation of manual call points on the same circuit as other actuating devices does not cause existing detector alarm indications to be extinguished; and (iii) that manual call points are not subjected to alarm dependency.
4 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING OF DOOR DEVICES - AS1670.1-2018: Check the operation of each device/door release once installed
5 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING CASCADE AND EWIS ZONING - AS1670.4-2018: Audible signals, visual and tactile signals to be checked – automatic operation.
6 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING SPEAKERS AND ZONES - AS1670.1-2018: Ensure Detectors are activated when tested and correctly indicates on the detectors and at the FDCIE

7 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING WARDEN INTERCOM PHONES - AS1670.4-2018: The WIP audible call signal shall have a SPL of not less than 80 dB(A) when measured at a distance of 1 m from the WIP. The SPL of the WIP handset audible call signal shall also be met when the WIP handset is mounted within a security enclosure.

8 - CONDUCT FIRE MATRIX TESTING - AS1670.1-2018: The ‘end-to-end’ test should include the activation of associated detection devices to confirm that all required functions operate correctly in accordance with the system interface matrix

9 - CONDUCT FIRE FAN CONTROL PANEL AND BRIGADE INTERFACE TESTING - AS1670.1-2018: The FFCP shall be incorporated into or located adjacent to the FBP and constructed in accordance with the FDCIE requirements in Clause 2.1
11 - CONDUCT FULL FUCNTIONAL FIRE TESTING AND WITNESSING - AS1670.4-2018 – 100% test of installed devices, Interface testing to Trades: Mech Shutdowns, Security trips

12 - SPRINKLER INTERFACES FITTED OFF - AS1670.1-2015: Systems interface testing Prior to any interface testing check that all systems listed in the system interface schedule are complete and operable. This will involve checking that all systems interfaces to the FDAS
13 - OPERATORS MANUAL, INSTALLERS STATEMENTS, AS- INSTALLED DRAWINGS, LOGBOOK AVAILABLE TO SPECIFICATION REQUIREMENTS - In House QA, Correct documentation, Referenced and submitted to PC

resource: ITPS-016 Fire and EWIS Panel Installation

column13: Check – Location - (i) Installed in a location protected by the FDAS (expect where external to building) (ii) Operation of FIP shall not affect evacuation of building (iii) Located in an area which presents low risk of damage to equipment and persons (iv) Not mounted in any rooms containing sprinkler, pumps or motors

Check – Particulars (i) Have controls and indicators not less than 750mm and not more than 1850mm above floor level. (ii) Have unobstructed access to controls and indicators (iii) Be mounted above ground level to protect batteries/on a plinth
Check – Where the FIP is obscured by a door ensure the words “FIRE PANEL” in letters not less than 50mm high. There SHALL be no other lettering on the door.
Check – Clearance. 1000mm in front of FIP and 500mm to each side shall be maintained.
Zone Block Plan – Installation shall be securely mounted and easily accessible.
Manual Call point – Manual call point must be installed at the entry point to site if the FIP is not located close to that point.
Check – Power cabling is installed at FIP location
Check – Location strobe on front of building is installed and operational.

resource: ITPS-016 Fire and EWIS Panel Installation

Tier 4: Check – Location - (i) Installed in a location protected by the FDAS (expect where external to building) (ii) Operation of FIP shall not affect evacuation of building (iii) Located in an area which presents low risk of damage to equipment and persons (iv) Not mounted in any rooms containing sprinkler, pumps or motors

Check – Particulars (i) Have controls and indicators not less than 750mm and not more than 1850mm above floor level. (ii) Have unobstructed access to controls and indicators (iii) Be mounted above ground level to protect batteries/on a plinth
Check – Where the FIP is obscured by a door ensure the words “FIRE PANEL” in letters not less than 50mm high. There SHALL be no other lettering on the door.
Check – Clearance. 1000mm in front of FIP and 500mm to each side shall be maintained.
Zone Block Plan – Installation shall be securely mounted and easily accessible.
Manual Call point – Manual call point must be installed at the entry point to site if the FIP is not located close to that point.
Check – Power cabling is installed at FIP location
Check – Location strobe on front of building is installed and operational.

Hold Point Details
Signatures
1 - CHECK SPRINKLER HEADS ARE INSTALLED IN AN ENVIRONMENT IN WHICH THEY ARE SUITED - AS2118.1-2017 – Section 2.2 – heads installed to correct classification and spacing

2 - CHECK HYDRANTS ARE INSTALLED TO CODE AND HAVE REQUIRED CLEARENCES - AS2419.1-2005 – Section 3.2 – Clearances differ when related to internal or external hydrants, ensure correct standards are implemented
3 - AIR TEST INSTALLATION BEFORE WATER FILL - AS2118.1-2017 – Section 7.9.4 – hold 300 kPa for 30 minutes without a 10% loss.
HOLD POINT
4 - STATIC TEST INSTALLATION WITH WATER TO 1600KPA - AS2118.1-2017 – Section 7 (7.9.3) – system tested to 1.6MPa and holds pressure for 2 hours
5 - CHECK & TEST WATER SUPPLY CAPACITY TO MEET SYSTEM DEMAND - AS2118.1-2017 - section 4.2.2.1 – capable of supplying the flow and pressure requirements of the sprinkler system.
6 - CHECK OPERATION OF PRESSURE SWITCHES TO DBS - AS2118.1-2017 - Appendix H4 – Test via 15mm test valve and record time taken to operate. Confirm with ASE monitoring service that alarm was received.
6 - CHECK OPERATION OF PRESSURE SWITCHES FOR PUMP START - AS2118.1-2017 – Appendix H5.4 – P/Sw to be tested via dropping system pressure via test valve or remote test point.

7 - CONDUCT 100% TESTING OF PRESSURE SWITCH, FLOW SWITCH & VALVE MONITOR - AS2118.1-2017 Appendix H6 – equipment to be tested to procedure set out in standard and in conjunction with Fire alarm workers.
8 - CHECK PUMP PRESSURE AND FLOW REQUIREMENTS - AS2118.1-2017 - Section 14.9 – shall be capable of satisfying the flow and pressure requirements of the design +50kPa.
9 - WITNESS TEST HOLD POINTS - PIPE TESTING PROCEDURE
HOLD POINT

10 - HYDROSTATIC SPRINKLER PIPE TEST - AS2118.1-2017 Appendix H & Section 7.9.3; All new installations, trunk mains and water supply connections shall be capable of withstanding for a period of 2 h, without loss of pressure, a hydrostatic test pressure of 1600 kPa.
HOLD POINT

resource: ITPS-014 Diesel Fire Pumpset Installation and Commissioning

Tier 4: 1 - Check location of pumpset - in a position that is protected from falling debris, and vehicular and mechanical damage - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 11 Installation

2 - Check clearance of pumpsets - For ongoing inspection and testing, a clearance of not less than 1.0 m shall be provided around the perimeter of a complete pump assembly; - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 11 Installation

3 - Check clearence of pumpset - for multiple pumpset installations, a clearance of not less than 600 mm between each of the installed pumps shall be provided - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 11 Installation

4 - Check elevations - Multiple pumpsets shall be installed with the centre-line of all suction pipes at the same elevation. If the pumps are to be installed at different elevations, the elevated pump shall be installed on a properly constructed mezzanine floor with head clearance of minimum 2.1 m to the underside on both levels - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 11 Installation

5 - Check Plinth - Pumpset baseplates shall be mounted on concrete plinths with a height not less than 150 mm above the floor. For fixing purposes, the concrete plinth shall extend 150 mm past the edge of the baseplate on all four sides. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 11 Installation
6a - Check the cooling supply system - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
6b - Check engine fuel supply - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
6c - Check the coupling alignment to ensure that the unit is aligned within the manufacturer’s specified tolerance - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
6d - Check the direction of rotation. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
6e - Check – Engine lubricating oil is at the correct level. Check – the battery electrolyte level and the battery leads and connections. Check – exhaust system is intact - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
6f - Ensure – pump is primed and that lines are clear, valves correctly set (open, closed, or adjusted to required pressure), and that water is available. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12

6g - Isolate – all other water supplies to the fire protection systems, such as the automatic pressure maintenance pump and any other compression-ignition engine driven pumps in the system. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
7a - Record – For automatic starting pumpsets, record the pressure in the system at which the pump starts automatically. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
7b - Record – Engine Oil Pressure - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
7c - Check – Coolant Flow is correct - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
7d - Check – That the fan is rotating and all fan belts are intact - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
7e - Record – pump shut-off pressure. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12

7f - Isolate – the flow meter, partially open the test valve, and flush to remove any debris or foreign matter; open any meter-isolating valves, open the test valve, and record pump delivery gauge pressure when approximately full load flow is indicated on the flow meter. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12

8 - Run the pump for 30 min at maximum flow and record the following: (i) Suction and delivery pressures. (ii) Engine running temperature, which shall be within the engine manufacturer’s recommended limits. (iii) Engine oil pressure, which shall be within the engine manufacturer’s limits. (iv) Air temperature at pumpset. (v) Discharge pressure at three other flow rates between shut-off and maximum flow, one of which shall be at the duty flow rate. (vi) Check that the requirements of Clause 9.3.6.2 are complied with by holding the engine shutdown mechanism closed and simulating an automatic start signal until the engine has attempted to start for five automatic starting cycles. On the sixth starting cycle, return the engine shutdown mechanism to its normal starting position and check if the engine starts immediately. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12

8a - During the operations in Item (h)— (A) periodically check temperature of the bearings and stuffing box leakage and note any abnormality; (B) check that all alarms and indicators, both visual and aural, have been activated; and (C) check that alarms and indicators, both visual and aural, revert to normal stand-by status when pump is stopped. If the pump failed to start alarms that are fitted on the pump fire pump controller and at the remote station, check that these alarms operate both aurally and visually. (j) Shut down and restore starting mechanism to stand-by status. (k) Restore power supply to the electric pumps and check correct status of indicators. - AS2941.1-2013 – Section 12
